726295f-b.title: Queens: Calamus Avenue - Elks Road
726295f-b.text:
Walamus Avenue, east from Elks Road to Grand Avenue, showing
in three views on the south side of the Avenue, partially sub-
merged, the Rapelye farmhouse. This house was renovated in 1923
and razed in early 1932. J. Gray was the owner from 1873 to 1891.
In 192E Fred Bushing was an occupant. Views one and two show
also a branch of the Long lIsland Railroad awd buildings on Grand
Avenue which ae seen at the right background.
June 19244
Viows 1,2 and 3
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726296f-a.title: Queens: Calamus Avenue - Elks Road
726296f-a.text:
Calamus Ave., south side, east from Elk Road to Grand Ave.,
showinc at the left, Nos. 7481 and 7442 Calamus Ave. In the backoround
on the east side of Grand Ave., are seen some two family frame struc-
tures. The peaked roof structure (clothing hanging On lines in back
thereof) was the orioinal Rapelje homesteadaand was in the hands of the
Gray family from 1873 to 1909; being demolished early in 1932. This is
a set of four views. In No. 4 may also be seen the steeple of St.
Alborts Church and the Brooklyn Union Gas Company's tanks.
May 1923.
View 2: March 1923.
View 3: January 1923.
View 4: May 1925.
Eucene L. Armbruster Collection.
